00:02:16.480 --> 00:02:20.120
&gt;&gt; Yeah, well I've been
working on two pieces

00:02:20.120 --> 00:02:24.980
for Carol since about 2008, 2009.

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:30.960
So tonight you'll hear the second
piece in a series of five pieces,

00:02:30.960 --> 00:02:34.930
so the series is entitled eyam.

00:02:34.930 --> 00:02:41.840 position:56%
And tonight's has a kind of subtitle
called Taking Apart Your Universe.

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:45.950
So Carol has played
the first piece eyam 1.

00:02:45.950 --> 00:02:48.640
It's a B flat clarinet solo.

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:51.140
She premiered that
a few years ago now.

00:02:51.140 --> 00:02:56.030
And then this piece tonight
kind of opens up that world

00:02:56.030 --> 00:03:03.410
of that first B flat clarinet
solo into the contrabass clarinet.

00:03:03.410 --> 00:03:09.310
And she has an ensemble of about
10 instruments surrounding her.

00:03:09.310 --> 00:03:12.020
So you'll see the contrabass
clarinet.

00:03:12.020 --> 00:03:15.270
It's a very unusual instrument.

00:03:15.270 --> 00:03:18.950
It plays as low as
the piano can play.

00:03:18.950 --> 00:03:23.030
So it's really earthy.

00:03:23.030 --> 00:03:24.840
So we really worked on the,

00:03:24.840 --> 00:03:29.720
I think when I met Carol she had
just bought the contrabass clarinet

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:32.360
when she played all the
other clarinets for years.

00:03:32.360 --> 00:03:36.880 position:56%
So I think we kind of really kind of
discovered the instrument together.

00:03:36.880 --> 00:03:42.190
Alas, like really it
has four octaves

00:03:42.190 --> 00:03:47.490 position:56%
from the very lowest you can imagine
to about say middle C. And then

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:49.720
after that you get higher register

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:53.950
but through harmonics
and multiphonics.

00:03:53.950 --> 00:03:58.000
So we kind of zoned into the
different colors of these registers

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.260
and then the ensemble
that's around her kind

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:03.550
of orchestrate these further.

00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:08.290
So we've worked on the color of the
instrument for a long time together

00:04:08.290 --> 00:04:11.860
to try and give it this
kind of extended life

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:16.230
that the ensemble gives
to it as well.

00:04:16.230 --> 00:04:18.770
&gt;&gt; It strikes me that I'm, I
just got to hear a little bit

00:04:18.770 --> 00:04:21.350
of the rehearsal, so it's my
first experience of the piece.

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:25.450
But it's, it strikes me that
you really kind of orchestrate

00:04:25.450 --> 00:04:28.300
out from the instrument into
the rest of the ensemble

00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:32.200
and we can really hear kind of a,
almost like a [inaudible] expansion

00:04:32.200 --> 00:04:36.090
into that space that's really
lovely and really nice.

00:04:36.090 --> 00:04:37.390
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:04:37.390 --> 00:04:38.690
&gt;&gt; Yeah, go ahead.

00:04:38.690 --> 00:04:41.800
&gt;&gt; Yeah, well I guess I'm
hugely interested in tanbur

00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:46.420 position:56%
and it's something very much I think
of the last century for composers

00:04:46.420 --> 00:04:49.650
to be interested in very kind

00:04:49.650 --> 00:04:52.960
of unique sound qualities
of certain instruments.

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:57.210 position:56%
And because this is, I guess quite a
new instrument and new for composers

00:04:57.210 --> 00:05:02.860
to be writing for it, when you
kind of zone in on different colors

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:07.810
of the instrument, they also, they
introduce a different sense of time

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:11.560
or you know, the way the
sound kind of buzzes.

00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:15.810
The low register is
so electronic almost.

00:05:15.810 --> 00:05:21.280
So that encourages you to, to
kind of think that way in terms

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:22.970
of orchestration as well.

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:25.030
So it's low register.

00:05:25.030 --> 00:05:32.160
I kind of batch with this trio of
bassoon, piano and double bass,

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:35.660
so they're very low with the
low register of the clarinet.

00:05:35.660 --> 00:05:39.640
And then the guitar is
matched with another,

00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:41.600
the next kind of part
of the register.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:47.990
And then there's a trio
of flute, cello and violin

00:05:47.990 --> 00:05:50.840
that are kind of the next octave.

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:57.820
And then the trumpet and the water
percussion are the highest octave.

00:05:57.820 --> 00:06:01.630
And the saxophone then,
kind of veers into this kind

00:06:01.630 --> 00:06:03.920
of multiphonic, kind
of harmonic area.

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:06.980
So really, I guess
with the ensemble I try

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:13.040
to almost reconstruct the color of
the entire register of the clarinet

00:06:13.040 --> 00:06:17.910
and just make it into
this huge clarinet.

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:21.860
&gt;&gt; And so you also use the
B flat clarinet as well?

00:06:21.860 --> 00:06:27.710
&gt;&gt; Yeah, a little bit of the B flat
and that kind of is trying to kind

00:06:27.710 --> 00:06:32.690
of bring us back to the solo
that opens the series of pieces.

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:37.670
So then this piece then
kind of expands on the solo.

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:40.600
&gt;&gt; Can you say a bit more about the
rest of the pieces in the series?

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:42.710
Are those already finished,
are they?

00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:47.870
&gt;&gt; You hear at the end of the this
piece tonight, the clarinet kind

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:51.510
of slowly hands its
powers over to the flute.

00:06:51.510 --> 00:06:55.080
[ Laughter ]

