So from there the flute pieces,

00:06:57.430 --> 00:07:01.290
the third piece is a
solo bass flute piece.

00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:05.180
Then the fourth one
is a contrabass flute,

00:07:05.180 --> 00:07:08.090
an ensemble, an electronics piece.

00:07:08.090 --> 00:07:13.440
And the last piece of the series
will be premiered in February

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:16.980
with Carol on contrabass clarinet.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:21.300
The contrabass flutist that I've
been working with Richard Craig

00:07:21.300 --> 00:07:25.460
and the RTE National
Symphony Orchestra in Dublin,

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:29.350
so it ends with the two
contras kind of meeting.

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:30.650
&gt;&gt; Oh wow.

00:07:30.650 --> 00:07:35.590 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Actually, I just want to mention.

00:07:35.590 --> 00:07:38.760
Professional musicians were
always working and very busy.

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:43.190
And Ann, we had a really
wonderful rehearsal period with Ann

00:07:43.190 --> 00:07:46.520
for the last 10 days
working on your music.

00:07:46.520 --> 00:07:50.360
But there's something
deeper actually.

00:07:50.360 --> 00:07:52.560
Carol has been our clarinetist

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:55.300
from the very beginning
and she is also Irish.

00:07:55.300 --> 00:07:58.590
And our Argento has gone
to Ireland many times

00:07:58.590 --> 00:08:00.280
and we have a relationship
with this country.

00:08:00.280 --> 00:08:04.910
And there's a very strong
of course literary tradition

00:08:04.910 --> 00:08:07.150
with [inaudible] and
Joyce and Yates.

00:08:07.150 --> 00:08:11.090
Many, many people who,
it's just in their blood.

00:08:11.090 --> 00:08:15.150
And I would love for you to tell
