00:11:15.810 --> 00:11:17.110
&gt;&gt; Yeah, absolutely.

00:11:17.110 --> 00:11:20.010
I mean, I love this
piece the Chirino piece.

00:11:20.010 --> 00:11:23.420
Actually for my doctoral studies,

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:26.400
it was one of the pieces I
chose to write a major paper.

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:31.220
So when Michel programmed it
with my piece, I was like wow.

00:11:31.220 --> 00:11:35.720
It was, I mean hearing Chirino's
music for the first time,

00:11:35.720 --> 00:11:37.720
I was totally blown away.

00:11:37.720 --> 00:11:42.360
I think it's, it's so bodily

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:47.310
and terribly I think
psychological as well.

00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:53.250
So it's definitely
an inspiration yeah.

00:11:53.250 --> 00:11:54.550
&gt;&gt; Maybe we can speak a bit more.

00:11:54.550 --> 00:11:58.220
We have maybe you can say a few
words about your pieces that are

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:01.470
on the first have Michel.

00:12:01.470 --> 00:12:06.910
&gt;&gt; You know, actually I think
I'll just say one thing.

00:12:06.910 --> 00:12:08.210
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:12.660
&gt;&gt; In terms of concert programming,
I always, there's a convention

00:12:12.660 --> 00:12:15.980
of intermissions and
I always have had

00:12:15.980 --> 00:12:18.840
for my whole life I've
had this feeling

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:23.350
that when there's an
intermission, whether we like it

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:25.150
or not, people socialize.

00:12:25.150 --> 00:12:28.690 position:56%
People go out and see their friends,
you know, they touch base with them.

00:12:28.690 --> 00:12:34.320
And somehow there's a need
to leave the realm of music.

00:12:34.320 --> 00:12:38.200
And so I never have you know,
when you accept that there's going

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:41.240
to be an intermission because we
don't have to have intermissions,

00:12:41.240 --> 00:12:44.570
that's already a convention
and when we accept

00:12:44.570 --> 00:12:48.660
that convention I always feel
like well we need some way

00:12:48.660 --> 00:12:52.870
of exiting the world of
music into the social world.

00:12:52.870 --> 00:12:58.620
Like and usually, so I always
like to choose an energetic piece.

00:12:58.620 --> 00:13:04.740
And I chose to program the solo
piano piece, because it has

00:13:04.740 --> 00:13:09.360
that kind of energy and some of
the other pieces like Ann's piece

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:14.160 position:56%
and Salvatore Chirino's piece, these
are pieces that end poetically,

00:13:14.160 --> 00:13:18.800
whistfully you know, quietly and
you know, at the end of pieces

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:22.860
like that, the last thing I
want to do is go socialize.

00:13:22.860 --> 00:13:28.280
So I tried to end first halves
of programs with energy.

00:13:28.280 --> 00:13:31.460
Something that's going to actually,

00:13:31.460 --> 00:13:34.590
something so that the
psychological mood you're

00:13:34.590 --> 00:13:38.200
in doesn't contradict you
know, socializing with friends,

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:40.310
you know, saying hi to friends.

00:13:40.310 --> 00:13:43.710
You know, so that's the reason
I programed the piano piece.

00:13:43.710 --> 00:13:46.760
I'd prefer to leave the clarinet
and piano piece as a surprise.

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:48.950
&gt;&gt; Sure, well maybe
you can say something

00:13:48.950 --> 00:13:52.650
about the title of the piano piece.

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:59.760
&gt;&gt; Oh, I think itself, not at all
to be cagey, not at all trust me.

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:05.690
I think it's, it's a
little bit pathological.

00:14:05.690 --> 00:14:07.950
I mean totally pathological.

00:14:07.950 --> 00:14:12.990
I think it'll speak for
itself, the way, the repetition

00:14:12.990 --> 00:14:15.260
and the layers and the obsession.

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:17.520
I think it'll speak for itself.

