Even though this is
great music but a lot

00:15:43.050 --> 00:15:47.030
of this music doesn't really feel
like it relates to modern life.

00:15:47.030 --> 00:15:52.790
It's more, you have to
experience it in a context.

00:15:52.790 --> 00:15:57.290
Whereas with Mahler I feel, I feel
when I'm working on his music,

00:15:57.290 --> 00:16:01.220
despite the ultra-romantic
surface of the music,

00:16:01.220 --> 00:16:04.940
I feel like I'm conducting
music that was written today.

00:16:04.940 --> 00:16:08.060
I don't know why, this is a
completely subjective thing,

00:16:08.060 --> 00:16:14.420 position:56%
but I feel like this guy understands
modern problems, modern dilemmas,

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:18.130
modern conflicts, frustrations.

00:16:18.130 --> 00:16:21.980
I don't know, he just
gets it, modern crisis.

00:16:21.980 --> 00:16:25.990
And for that reason
I've been quite obsessed

00:16:25.990 --> 00:16:30.160
with his works for a long time now.

00:16:30.160 --> 00:16:35.800
The Tenth Symphony is something
that's particularly problematic

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:37.350
because it's unfinished.

00:16:37.350 --> 00:16:43.290
And there's some very strange
things in the manuscript,

00:16:43.290 --> 00:16:46.360
basically when Mahler
died he left five folders,

00:16:46.360 --> 00:16:52.930
each folder with sketches and
short score from beginning to end

00:16:52.930 --> 00:16:56.490
of a movement, one of
his five movements.

00:16:56.490 --> 00:17:02.130
And the second movement has,
has scherzo finale written

00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:03.430
which is a contradiction

00:17:03.430 --> 00:17:06.760
because there's also the fifth
movement is also a finale.

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:11.880
So a scherzo is a contrasting
movement that has a binary form

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:15.560
and is largely transitional
into a finale most

00:17:15.560 --> 00:17:18.120
of the time in classical form.

00:17:18.120 --> 00:17:21.800
So to say scherzo finale
doesn't really make any sense,

00:17:21.800 --> 00:17:27.700
but he wrote this very
clearly and it became clearer

00:17:27.700 --> 00:17:32.140
as I was studying some other
scholars work on this piece

00:17:32.140 --> 00:17:36.760
that Mahler was really thinking of
this piece as a two part symphony.

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:39.520
One part being the
first two movements

00:17:39.520 --> 00:17:42.400
and the second part being
the last three movements.

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:47.100
And that the second movement
really answers the first.

00:17:47.100 --> 00:17:55.280
So I did the best I could to retain
the spirit of Mahler as I see it.

00:17:55.280 --> 00:18:00.620 position:56%
And put these two movements together
as one unit for a listening audience

00:18:00.620 --> 00:18:04.540
for years, so that's basically
the story of the piece.

00:18:04.540 --> 00:18:07.110
